   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="edition"><!-- transcription goes here -->
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/>Θεοῖς <expan>
                  <abbr>Καταχθ<hi rend="small">ον</hi>
                  </abbr>
                  <ex>ίοις</ex>
               </expan>
               <lb n="2"/>
               <persName>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Onesicrates">Ὀνησικράτου</name>
                  <lb n="3"/>
                  <name type="ethnonym" key="Nicomedes">Νεικομηδέος</name>
               </persName>.
                    <lb n="4"/>
               <persName>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Zoilus">Ζωίλος</name>
               </persName> συνπο
                    <lb n="5" break="no"/>λείτης ἐπόησε
                    <lb n="6"/>μνήμης ἕνεκα
                    <lb n="7"/>ὑπὲρ <hi rend="tall">φ</hi>ίλου, <expan>
                  <abbr>ζήσαντ</abbr>
                  <ex>ος</ex>
               </expan>
               <lb n="8"/>ἔτη <num value="60">Ξ</num>. Χαίρετε.
                </ab>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p> To the gods of the underworld of Onesicrates of Nicomedia. Zoilos, (his) fellow
                    townsman made (this) as a memorial for his friend, (who) lived for 60 years.
                    Farewell.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary"><!-- notes go here -->
            <p>Line 1: small and raised -ον- mark the only abbreviation which expands to complete
                    the plural masculine dative adjective of the common epitaph formula. </p>
            <p>Lines 2-3: ‘Ονησικράτου Νεικομηdέος is attested also in the epitaph of his son
                    Proklos, IG 14.876b (=MI.AA.UM.KM.G.1108), also from Misenum and the De Criscio
                    collection.; Νεικομηδεος for Νεικομηδεως. </p>
            <p>Line 4: Ζωίλος is a fairly common Greek name, presumably his townsman of
                    Nicomedia in Asia minor. </p>
            <p>Line 7: φίλου is marked by a dot over the upsilon although no other accents or
                    diacritics are indicated. </p>
            <p>Fine-grained gray marble.</p>
         </div>
